Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Surely the state veterinarian was also encouraging equine owners to vaccine against West Nile Virus. The WNV vaccine is usually combined with eastern and western equine encephalitis and tetanus. This is a lot of protection for an injection, given twice, about 3-4 weeks apart. Please vaccinate your animals and eliminate water holes where mosquitoes can breed. This may be small puddles, the catch dish on potted plants, inside of tires, and other places were even a small amount of water is left standing. Use equine approved spray to prevent mosquito and fly bites. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5366699,244.]
